mediaobject.caption:
Different artificial noise applied to the same surface:
symmetrical Gaussian noise (left);
positive exponential noise (centre);
negative exponential noise (right).
All images have the same false colour scale and all noises have the
same RMS.

Different types of line noise added to an artificial pyramidal surface.
Top row:
unmodified surface (left);
relatively sparse cumulative steps (centre);
relatively sparse ridges (right).
Bottom row:
scars of mean length of 16 px and high coverage (left);
tilt with small offset dispersion (centre);
hum with default settings (right).

Artificial columnar surfaces: loosely packed columns (left);
tightly packed columns (centre); directional growth with strong
relaxation (right).

Artificial surfaces created by ballistic deposition:
initial stage with relatively small correlation length (left);
after correlations reached image size (centre);
deposition starting from a microchip surface (right).

Artificial domain surfaces: spiral waves with long-range order
(left);
short-range ordered spiral waves at a higher temperature (centre);
the continous variable for a low-temperature situation with
small strength and coupling (right).

Artificial lattice surfaces: faceted surface created by
random linear interpolation (left);
bumps in a distorted triangular pattern (centre);
distorted rectangular pattern with segments separated by trenches
(right).

Artificial Brownian surfaces:
classic surface generated with H about 0.7 (left);
nebula-like image generated with a heavy-tailed power distribution
(centre);
the effect of small stationarity scale (right).

Artificial two-phase images:
small size spread (left);
larger size spread (right).

Artificial disc images:
round discs with some height distribution (left);
transformation to tiles (centre);
erosion by opening filter (right).

Dune images:
the default settings (left);
long flat dunes with small maximum slope (centre);
more isotropic dunes for highly random wind direction (right).

Plateau images:
the default settings (left);
approximately self-affine surface with small scaling power and minimum size (centre);
somewhat overlapping irregular flakes (right).

Wetting front images:
a typical result with moderate coverage (left);
initial stage of propagation (right).
